  keywords      = {rank4, read},
  publisher     = {World Scientific Pub Co Pte Lt},
  review        = {In this paper the authors use machine learning for a smart fire detection system. Their approach combines an integrated sensor system (smoke, heat and flame detectors) that monitors a room, sending sensing data to a micro-controller. Instead of just comparing the sensed values with a set of thresholds, machine learning algorithms analyze the measurements and output the fire danger level. When the fire danger level raises above a potential level threshold, camera sensors sends images of the scene to the micro-controller that, once again, makes use of machine learning algorithms to analyze the image and enhance the fire danger level. If the system detects fire, some automatic actions are performed: cut off electric power, turn on sprinkles, alarm and notifies authorities via a GSM module. The authors compared 16 machine learning algorithms against a dataset of 102 samples and found out that in all measures LMT, MultilayerPerceptron and SimpleLogistics algorithms showed 100% accuracy. They argue that by using machine learning algorithms to validate sensing data the system can procude appropriate outputs and eliminate false alarms.

