  year          = {2018},
  volume        = {31},
  pages         = {1166-1176},
  note          = {00008},
  document_type = {Article},
  doi           = {10.1016/j.ijdrr.2017.09.032},
  keywords      = {rank3, read},
  review        = {In this paper the authors propose a framework for risk reduction for indoor parking facilities. The goal is to reduce the evacuation time in a exceeding capacity parking facility in case of an emergency. The authors argue that while it is easy to implement positioning solutions in outdoor environments, indoor scenarios pose more difficulty because of constraints that are leveraged by large obstacles as walls and others cars. This framework then uses several technologies for cars positioning: RFID, Wi-Fi hotspots, bluetooth and UWB devices. Also, smartphones inside the vehicles have been used to detect acceleration and deacceleration. To evalueate the approach, the authors first tested the technologies in a real environment, using a multi-level parking facility and ten vehicles. They deployed several RFIDs sensors, Wi-Fi, bluetooth and UWB hardware along the parking to detect the position of the cars. The tests had shown that the use of these technologies makes it possible: the RFID tags inside the vehicles could inform their position in a feasible accuracy while the UWB hardware was capable of detecting their movements. For a final evaluation, they simulated this environment using AIMSUN simulator, MATLAB and Python scripts for four scenarios: normal operation (vehicles must use the regular exits of the parking facility to evacuate), ramp reversal scenario (vehicles are allowed to use the ramps for evacuation), counter flow (in addition of using ramps, the vehicles can also use the entrances for evacuation) and counter flow plus two lanes (the corridors of the parking facility are used as two lanes). The simulations have shown that there is a decrease between 34.74% and 42.31% in evacuation time comparing the counter flow plus two lanes scenario with normal operation. The authors argue that these positioning technologies are suitable for the task of planing evacuation strategies in indoor environments.

Kind of approach: sensing + mitigation},
  source        = {Scopus},
}

