of smartphone technologies and geographic services

In this paper the authors propose a crowdsource mapping approach to provide geolocation of buildings in harzard. They developed a smartphone app so volunteer users can use it when facing a building in harzard. When an user gets close to such event, it can then run the app to collect positional information, take photos and send to a central database that will contain information about the emergency. To properly get the correct location, the app can use GPS for initial positioning and then, the user can improve the positioning by choosing a point on the map, entering geocoding information such as address or use the device's camera, accelerometer and mangnetic sensor, so that the app will try to calculate the user's distance from the building. This correction is necessary because when facing a building in harzard, the users will not get too close for his/her own safety, thus, the GPS sensor will not get the precise position. By collecting data from volunteers, a central service can be notified on the occurence of an emergency and get the exact location for first responders. Seventeen volunteers were given the experimental app to test it and answer a questionnari to evaluate the system. 82\% of respondents agreed or totally agreed that this approach is preferable over telephone communication for emergencies alerting and 94\% agreed or totally agreed that this system could complement the current disaster information systems.

