  review        = {In this paper the authors propose a discrete-event-based simulation model (DEBS) to predict restoration time after an earthquake event. Restoration time is the time required after the occurence of an emergency event for the resources to arrive at the event site and restore it to a stable situation. The authors model is based on their previous work presented in [xx], involving state transitions to model the event and calculate the restoration time. In their approach, they consider fire, gas leakage, building collapsing and flooding events, being flooding considered in a secondary state, i.e., the worst kind of incident. Their model was implemented using MATLAB and 1,000,000~h of simulation time was performed in a low probability of flooding scenario in St. Louis, USA. The simulation has shown that as more resources are used to mitigate the situation, less response time is required. The travel time, i.e., the time needed to travel from the resources center to the crisis area, has little influence in the resulting restoration time compared to the number of resources available. This behavior was the same in a high probability of flooding scenario. The authors argue that their model is helpful in smart cities initiatives to previously plan and predict mitigation efforts in emergency situations.

Kind of approach: mitigation},
  source        = {Scopus},
}

