  keywords      = {rank4, read},
  publisher     = {{SAGE} Publications},
  review        = {In this paper the authores propose an indepentent system for victims health monitoring and localization in a post-earthquake scenario. Communication infrastructure as Wi-Fi and mobile phone networks may be unavaiable after an earthquake, thus, the proposed system does not rely on such infrastrucuture to operate. The system then uses fixed anchors inside the monitored building that communicate to wearable tags using an autonomous ultra-wide band (UWB) network. The tag is also a health monitor, that senses user's heart rate and oximetry. In this way, the system can not only localize victims after a disaster but also monitors their health status, making it possible to prioritize most injured users. To gather the data inside the building, ZigBee routers forward data to an external coordinator, which feeds a graphical application that can be used by rescuers to localize the victims in a map and monitor their health status. All the hardware are battery-powered, so it does not depend on mains power supply. To evaluate their proposal, the authors implemented the system and tested it inside the Geotechnical and Building Engineering at the Technical University of Turin, Italy. Eight anchors were positioned in a corridor and two participants were wearing tags. The graphical application could properly localize the participants and monitor their health conditions. Also, the system had an accuraacy of 46.5\~cm at a 15\~distance. They also tested their system in a large room, in which it had an accuracy of 54\~cm at the same distance.

Kind of approach: mitigation},
  source        = {Scopus},
}

