  review        = {In this paper the authors propose the Smart Box, a sensing solution to monitor the environment and act as a node in a mesh network for post-disaster communications. Smart Box is a sensing hardware which contains air quality sensors, long range Wi-Fi networking and a tablet device to manage data and networking, and it is powered by solar panels and a wind harverster. This device have two working modes: normal operation and emergency operation. In normal operation, the Smart Box acts as a sensing node, collecting air quality data and sending to a central application. In emergency mode, the device switchs to an access point state, enabling first responders and citizens to connect to its Wi-Fi mesh networking and have connectivity in a post-disaster scenario, when ordinary communication infrastructure may be in a failing state. To achieve this goal, the tens or hunderds of Smart Boxes must be deployed in the city, so they can connect to each other forming a Wi-Fi mesh network. If any intermediate Smart Box fails, preventing the connection of two sets of nodes, these clusters operate apart, so first responders can still have some communication. Their solution can be of greate help in a post-disaster scenarion, when ordinary communication infrastructure may not work.

